    pearls: ["Gastroparesis diagnosis requires: (1) symptoms of gastric retention, (2) objective delayed emptying on scintigraphy, AND (3) absence of mechanical obstruction on EGD; all three criteria must be met","Postoperative ileus >5 days is considered prolonged; evaluate for complications (anastomotic leak, abscess, electrolyte imbalance) and consider CT imaging","Ogilvie syndrome: neostigmine 2 mg IV over 3-5 minutes is the pharmacological treatment of choice; requires cardiac monitoring (risk of bradycardia); atropine at bedside; colonoscopic decompression if neostigmine fails","Metoclopramide is the ONLY FDA-approved medication for gastroparesis; tardive dyskinesia risk is cumulative and may be irreversible; always discuss risk-benefit with patients","Hyperactive, high-pitched bowel sounds with rushes suggest mechanical obstruction (peristalsis against obstruction); absent bowel sounds suggest ileus or late obstruction; this auscultatory distinction is clinically important","GLP-1 receptor agonists (semaglutide, liraglutide) delay gastric emptying as part of their mechanism; they can unmask or worsen gastroparesis and should be avoided in patients with known delayed gastric emptying"],
